\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*What is segregation?: Previous studies -> Frank showed that the most relevant
 quantity for the segregation is the accretion redshift; Adhikari et al.
 2016
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
* We investigate the mass dependence of segregation and its observational
 signature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
*Assembly History affects to clusterings as well as internal structure:
 Miyatake et al.
 2015 (detection of assembly bias) & More et al.
 2016 (subhalo distribution with concentration)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
-> Does assembly history matter for segregation?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mass Dependence of Segregation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate the mass dependence of segregation by comparing
 the radial distribution of subhalos in the host halos with different masses.
 To do that, we first select host halos based on their halo masses such
 that their halo masses in samples are from 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, from 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, and greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, for each sample, we split their corresponding subhalos based on the
 accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

).
 Using those subsamples, we compute the radial distances normalized by their
 virial radius.
 Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radial_massDependence"

\end_inset

 shows histograms of the radial distribution for early and late accreted
 subhalos split at 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 The solid lines are for the subhalos in the host halos whose masses are
 greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, while circles and dashed lines correspond to the host halos whose masses
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=[10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}},10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=[10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}},10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}]$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 The figure indicates that there is no mass dependence on segregation.
\end_layout

