\begin_layout Subsection
Correlation between 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tidal stripping is a phenomenon that the subhalos experience mass loss due
 to tidal forces of their host halos.
 As a general trend, subhalos which are accreted earlier experience more
 mass loss due to tidal stripping.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The retaining mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 are the subhalo masses at present time and at accretion, indicates the
 amount of mass loss after subhalos are accreted by their host halos.
 The question is how well this property 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 correlates with the accretion redshift 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:correlation"

\end_inset

 shows correlation of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 as well as with 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,acc}}$
\end_inset

 are the maximum circular velocity at present time and at accretion.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are tightly correlated with 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is expected, because the subhalos which are accreted earlier must
 be striped more mass due to tidal stripping.
 Quantitatively, the cross correlation coefficients for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is 0.651, while it is 0.403 for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

.
 As is clear from the figures, the change in halo mass is larger than the
 change in the maximum circular velocity.
 This is mostly because approximately the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}\propto M_{{\rm vir}}^{1/3}$
\end_inset

 holds.
 Applying this scaling relation and converting 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

, the slope for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm vir}}/m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is steeper than the slope for 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 (the slope for mass is -0.3035, while the slope for Vmax is -2.006...but this
 is mostly due to the subhalos whose Vmax change is drastic).
 Those results are not consistent with the results in Ref.
 xxx [vdB, Figure 5].
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color red
This actually throws some doubt on the picture that tidal stripping removes
 the mass of the subhalos from their outer regions and therefore the change
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 is smaller.
 (This statement is not made in any references for subhalos...Read vdB's potential
 depth paper and Arthur's paper to confirm the picture, at least this says
 that tidal stripping strip the matter not only from outer regions...)
\end_layout

