\begin_layout Subsection
Observational Signature: correlation functions in redshift-space & projected
 ones...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Effects of Assembly Bias on Segregation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we investigate whether the assembly history of the host
 halos affects the subhalo mass functions and spatial distribution of the
 subhalos.
 To test this, we first select cluster-sized halos (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}>10^{14}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

) and split them based on their concentration.
 We use the median concentration-mass relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}})$
\end_inset

 shown in Ref.xxx (Dutton_macciio14): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\rm log}_{10}\bar{c}=-0.097{\rm log_{10}M_{vir}}+2.148.\label{eq:concen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For every halo in the Bolshoi catalogs, we use its tabulated 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}}),$
\end_inset

 and then use the values 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}$
\end_inset

 to compare with the measured concentration for every halo.
 We will henceforth refer to halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $c<\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low-concentration halos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $c>\bar{c}(M_{{\rm vir}})$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high-concentration halos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:subhaloMassFn"

\end_inset

 shows unevolved and evolved subhalo mass functions for high/low-concentration
 host halos.
 Both subhalo mass functions indicate that the subhalo mass functions for
 high-concentration halos have fewer subhalos for 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm acc}}/M_{{\rm vir}}>10^{-1.5}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 is the subhalo mass at accretion and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 is the host halo mass at present.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the same samples of halos, we split subhalos based on 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{{\rm acc}}$
\end_inset

 and compare their radial distributions as shown in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:radialDist_concen"

\end_inset

.
 While the subhalos which are accreted after 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.5$
\end_inset

 (or the subhalos which have not lost much mass) do not exhibit any difference
 in the spatial distribution for the high/low-concentration host halos,
 the subhalos which are accreted before 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.5$
\end_inset

 have similar inner distribution but diffrent outer distributions.
